WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.480
So why don't we start with the museum?

00:00:02.480 --> 00:00:06.560
Can you remember what did you see in the museum and what did it remind you of?

00:00:06.560 --> 00:00:14.240
Yeah, when we came to the museum and we went upstairs,

00:00:14.240 --> 00:00:19.840
we saw the lady was doing the wool and knitting.

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:24.560
So this is reminded me from my childhood.

00:00:24.800 --> 00:00:32.320
So when we were in the school, we finished the school, our uncle used,

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:39.040
when we come back from the school, our uncle said sit down and start doing the knitting

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:45.440
and do the baskets and the mat,

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:52.080
sitting mats, we have to make it.

00:00:52.960 --> 00:01:00.080
So we have to climb all the way because we have lots of date tree very long.

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:06.080
So we somebody have to climb and take it out the leaves because the leaves is very strong.

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:14.960
And we do the, I don't know what you call for, you know, you do.

00:01:14.960 --> 00:01:16.800
Knitting or weaving?

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:18.000
Weaving, I think.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.960
Yeah. So we have to make it one by one.

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:29.200
Like you do with the hair, plaiting, plaiting, sorry.

00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:35.440
We have to do that one and make it one by one and attach to each other.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.240
But it takes us a whole day to make one.

00:01:41.200 --> 00:01:54.080
And then we, when we finish this one, go back home and then study for one hour.

00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:57.600
And then tomorrow early morning, we have to again wake up.

00:01:58.480 --> 00:02:04.800
So we didn't have chance to play or speak friends or something like that.

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:15.760
But it was reminded me of my childhood, how we was working hard for little things.

00:02:16.640 --> 00:02:22.240
So it's really nice when I went over in the museum.

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:28.560
And also when we went around and see different clothes.

00:02:29.520 --> 00:02:43.200
So we used to have the small, we sit down like with my auntie, mother, my sisters.

00:02:43.200 --> 00:02:57.440
And they, the person bring us like clothes where you have to do the designs.

00:02:58.720 --> 00:02:59.680
Immortary.

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:06.160
So he bring small, small bits, different colors, and he give us the design.

00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:08.000
So we have to do this one.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:11.920
It take us like two weeks to finish whole dress.

00:03:12.640 --> 00:03:14.400
Somebody bring their weddings.

00:03:15.280 --> 00:03:18.400
Somebody bring their traditional dress to do it.

00:03:19.120 --> 00:03:28.480
But we have to put it in the wooden, square wooden.

00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:37.520
Have to put that clothes in and then we have to, that material and then we do the sewing.

00:03:38.400 --> 00:03:38.640
Yeah.

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:44.800
So it's really remind me lots of things when I came to the museum.

00:03:48.640 --> 00:03:51.120
So the baskets and the mats.

00:03:51.120 --> 00:03:51.360
Yeah.

00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:55.840
What are the, what's the traditional word for that in your language?

00:03:56.320 --> 00:03:59.680
It's, and you're speaking Arabic?

00:03:59.680 --> 00:04:00.080
Arabic.

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:00.320
Yeah.

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:01.360
What's the word in Arabic?

00:04:01.360 --> 00:04:07.760
The mat called Sijada and the basket called Silla in Arabic.

00:04:07.760 --> 00:04:10.880
Were they, were you, was your uncle making them?

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:12.800
Why was he making them and why were you making them?

00:04:12.800 --> 00:04:14.000
Was it to sell them?

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:18.320
Yeah, to sell them and get some money from it.

00:04:18.320 --> 00:04:18.560
Yeah.

00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:21.680
And also we have something called Fokhar.

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:22.960
Fokhar.

00:04:22.960 --> 00:04:27.920
It's with the, we make it with the,

00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:41.520
you know when you make with your hand,

00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:47.360
like a vase and cups.

00:04:47.360 --> 00:04:47.840
Mud.

00:04:47.840 --> 00:04:48.320
Clay?

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:48.640
Clay.

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:53.120
We used to sit down and make that one.

00:04:53.120 --> 00:04:54.320
Okay.

00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:55.120
Also to sell?

00:04:55.760 --> 00:04:57.040
Also to sell, yeah.

00:04:57.840 --> 00:05:03.360
So he have a like in the road, he sit down and sell this kind of things.

00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:08.720
So we have, we used to help him all the time to do the, with the clay maker,

00:05:09.200 --> 00:05:15.680
the cups, plates and also we make the pot to cook the food.

00:05:18.720 --> 00:05:24.320
When you cook this food in this pot, which we make it with our hand,

00:05:25.200 --> 00:05:31.440
it makes really delicious food and you can feel that deliciousness and

00:05:32.080 --> 00:05:35.360
when it cooked inside it, you,

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:39.200
food is different.

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:42.160
You cannot taste this kind of food anywhere else.

00:05:42.960 --> 00:05:43.200
Yeah.

00:05:44.640 --> 00:05:48.640
So he had lots of, lots of skills, dressmaking.

00:05:49.280 --> 00:05:49.780
Yeah.

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:57.280
We used to do this, like a woman used to do the clothes making, the knitting ones.

00:05:58.240 --> 00:06:10.640
And with my uncles, we used to do the clay ones, make it and also the baskets and the mats.

00:06:11.840 --> 00:06:12.340
Yeah.

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:14.960
So you said you were working hard.

00:06:15.600 --> 00:06:16.000
Yeah.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:18.640
Yeah. And because you weren't very, very old.

00:06:19.280 --> 00:06:19.760
No.

00:06:19.760 --> 00:06:25.600
Can you tell me a bit more about how old you were, who you were doing it with and how it felt to do

00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:27.280
handicrafts?

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:38.160
We were around eight to nine years old and sit with my uncles and we used to

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:47.600
make it, but it feels like when I see my friends, they are playing, they call me and they say,

00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:53.040
come we can play, but we was like, you know, forced to do something.

00:06:53.600 --> 00:06:54.800
So it's really hard.

00:06:56.640 --> 00:07:03.280
Our hands used to pain and even we tell them, they say, no, you have to do it because if we

00:07:03.280 --> 00:07:11.920
don't do it from where we can get money or how we survive, you know, so we used to help and do

00:07:12.960 --> 00:07:14.720
the things they say us to do.

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:20.400
Was that normal for children to be working like that?

00:07:21.040 --> 00:07:30.880
Not all. Some of them. Other of my friends, they didn't force, but our situation maybe was

00:07:30.880 --> 00:07:36.320
difficult and hard, so we have to do to help them.

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:43.840
So was there anything else at the museum? You said it was the lady spinning the wool

00:07:43.840 --> 00:07:47.520
or was it the weaving that reminded you of the basket weaving?

00:07:48.080 --> 00:07:48.960
Basket weaving.

00:07:49.680 --> 00:07:53.280
But which object was it that you saw that reminded you of that?

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:02.560
The one she was, like a wheel and she was doing in the, her

00:08:04.560 --> 00:08:13.920
tie. She was doing it, so it's reminded because we got lots of sheep, animals, so we do have to

00:08:14.880 --> 00:08:29.120
cut their skin, the wool, and bring it and then we give it. So they teach us how to do, help them.

00:08:30.960 --> 00:08:37.280
So you would do the thigh ones. Can you tell me a bit more about how you would make the yarn

00:08:37.920 --> 00:08:39.040
and then what you would do with it?

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:47.120
They make it, they do it with the tie, but make it,

00:08:53.200 --> 00:09:00.400
so they do it with their tie, make it very thin so they can then use it for the sewing as well

00:09:00.400 --> 00:09:05.440
for the clothing and doing other stuff with it.

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:08.880
So you would use that to sew on the clothes?

00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:09.440
Yes.

00:09:09.440 --> 00:09:11.440
Would you also knit with it?

00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:22.080
Knit, we do it, but that will be like our mother, they knit the clothes like my mother,

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:34.080
she make for my son a hat and she send it over, so all three of my children, they share it.

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:38.640
And they wear the hats.

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:43.840
I remember them telling you about that on the day, they were very sweet.

00:09:46.800 --> 00:09:50.320
They were very excited and happy to tell you their story.

00:09:51.040 --> 00:09:55.280
So I think in future it's something to think about if we can do it with the kids.

00:09:55.280 --> 00:10:03.840
And also you know with the hat, the Arab people wear it, so we do sew that one as well,

00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:14.720
but it will be like designs and it will be holes, so you just take the needle and sew it,

00:10:14.720 --> 00:10:19.520
but different, different color. It will be like in the paper, in the picture they show you,

00:10:19.520 --> 00:10:20.640
and you have to do that.

00:10:23.120 --> 00:10:27.200
So this one, the main whale that had, yeah.

00:10:27.200 --> 00:10:29.040
Were you making those when you were younger too?

00:10:29.040 --> 00:10:29.540
Yeah.

00:10:29.700 --> 00:10:30.200
Yeah.

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:35.700
Is there anything else you'd like to tell me about the museum trip,

00:10:35.700 --> 00:10:37.700
things you saw, things you were reminded of?

00:10:38.820 --> 00:10:48.100
The museum have reminded a lot of things, like you know the wooden design of it,

00:10:48.100 --> 00:10:54.820
so it reminds us like our houses was like you know, big space,

00:10:55.700 --> 00:11:05.700
and all the things, most of the things over there like a blanket, old blankets, yeah.

00:11:06.340 --> 00:11:15.620
